'''''{{lang|de|Ich lebe, mein Herze, zu deinem Erg<U+00F6>tzen}}''''' (I live, my heart, for your delight), '''BWV 145''', is a [[Bach cantata|church cantata]] for [[Easter]] by [[Johann Sebastian Bach]]. He composed it in [[Leipzig]] and likely first performed it in 1729.

== History and words ==

The cantata is extant only in a later copy. The text of five movements for the [[Church cantata (Bach)#Easter Tuesday|Third Day of Easter]] ("{{lang|de|den dritten Osterfesttag}}") was published in [[Picander]]'s annual volume of cantatas of 1728, therefore a first performance on 19 April 1729 seems likely.<ref name="D<U+00FC>rr" /><ref name="Hofmann" />

The prescribed readings for the feast day were from the [[Acts of the Apostles]], the sermon of [[Paul the Apostle|Paul]] in Antiochia ({{Sourcetext|source=Bible|version=King James|book=Acts|chapter=13|verse=26|range=<U+2013>33}}), and from the [[Gospel of Luke]], the [[Resurrection appearances of Jesus|appearance of Jesus]] to the [[Apostle (Christian)|Apostles]] in [[Jerusalem]] ({{Sourcetext|source=Bible|version=King James|book=Luke|chapter=24|verse=36|range=<U+2013>47}}). The five movements on Picander's text seem rather short for the purpose, therefore [[Alfred D<U+00FC>rr]] suggests that Bach might have added a [[sinfonia]], as in two cantatas of the period, [[BWV 174]] and BWV 188, admitting that there is no source to substantiate it. Instead, in the copy the five Picander movement are preceded by two movements, a four-part of the first stanza of [[Caspar Neumann]]'s chorale "{{lang|de|Auf, mein Herz, des Herren Tag}}" (ca. 1700), and then the first movement from a cantata by [[Georg Philipp Telemann]], "{{lang|de|So du mit deinem Munde bekennest Jesum}}", a paraphrase of {{Sourcetext|source=Bible|version=King James|book=Romans|chapter=10|verse=9}}. The beginning of the latter is the title of the copy. The two movements may have been added after Bach's death to make the cantata fit to be performed on Easter Sunday. Picander did not refer to the specific readings for the Third Day of Easter in his text.<ref name="D<U+00FC>rr" /> According to [[Klaus Hofmann]], [[Carl Philipp Emanuel Bach]] expanded the cantata by the two additional movements in Hamburg (after 1768) and set the first movement himself.<ref name="Hofmann" /> According to [[Christoph Wolff]], the cantata may have been compiled by [[Carl Friedrich Zelter]] for the [[Sing-Akademie zu Berlin]].<ref name="Wolff" /> The closing chorale is the fourteenth and final stanza of [[Nikolaus Herman]]'s Easter hymn "{{lang|de|Erschienen ist der herrlich Tag}}".<ref name="chorale text" />

== Scoring and structure ==

The cantata is scored for three vocal soloists ([[soprano]], [[tenor]] and [[Bass (voice type)|bass]]), a [[SATB|four-part choir]], [[trumpet]], [[flauto traverso]], two [[oboe d'amore]], two [[violin]]s, [[viola]] and [[Figured bass#Basso continuo|basso continuo]].<ref name="D<U+00FC>rr" />

# Chorale: ''{{lang|de|Auf, mein Herz, des Herren Tag}}''
# Chorus: ''{{lang|de|So du mit deinem Munde bekennest Jesum}}'' (Telemann)

# Aria (tenor, soprano): ''{{lang|de|Ich lebe, mein Herze, zu deinem Erg<U+00F6>tzen}}''
# Recitative (tenor): ''{{lang|de|Nun fordre, Moses, wie du willt}}''
# Aria (bass): ''{{lang|de|Merke, mein Herze, best<U+00E4>ndig nur dies}}''
# Recitative (soprano): ''{{lang|de|Mein Jesus lebt}}''
# Chorale: ''{{lang|de|Drum wir auch billig fr<U+00F6>hlich sein}}''

== Music ==

The first added movement is a four-part setting of the chorale stanza. The Telemann movement is in two parts, a duet and a choral [[fugue]], with strings and instruments [[colla parte]] and a partly independent trumpet. In Telemann's cantata, it was preceded by an instrumental introduction on the same theme.<ref name="D<U+00FC>rr" />

The music on Picander's text begins in movement 3, a [[duet]] with [[obbligato]] violin. The tenor expresses the position of Jesus "{{lang|de|Ich lebe, mein Herze, zu deinem Erg<U+00F6>tzen}}" (I live, my heart, for your pleasure), whereas the soprano answers as the believer: "{{lang|de|Du lebest, mein Jesu, zu meinem Erg<U+00F6>tzen}}" (You live, my Jesus, for my pleasure). The movement resembles duets of Bach's secular cantatas and is possibly the [[Parody music|parody]] of an unknown work.<ref name="D<U+00FC>rr" /> It is unusual that Bach has the tenor represent the [[Vox Christi|voice of Jesus]].<ref name="Hofmann" /><ref name="Mincham" /> The following secco [[recitative]] ends as an [[arioso]] to stress the words "{{lang|de|Mein Herz, das merke dir!}}" (My heart, take note!), a thought picked up in the following bass [[aria]], the movement with the richest instrumentation, all instruments but the viola. It has the character of a dance in even periods<ref name="D<U+00FC>rr" /> and may also be a parody of a secular work.<ref name="Hofmann" /><ref name="Mincham" /> The cantata is closed by a four-part setting of the last stanza of the Easter chorale "{{lang|de|Erschienen ist der herrlich Tag}}".<ref name="chorale melody" />

